SIMPLE: wilderness
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wilderness
<hw>Wil"der*ness</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wildernesse</ets>, <ets>wilderne</ets>,probably from AS.
<ets>wildor</ets> a wild beast; cf. D. <ets>wildernis</ets> wilderness.
See <er>Wilder</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A tract of land, or a region, uncultivated and
uninhabited by human beings, whether a forest or a wide, barren plain; a
wild; a waste; a desert; a pathless waste of any kind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The wat'ry <qex>wilderness</qex> yields no supply.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A disorderly or neglected place.</def>
<rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Quality or state of being wild; wildness.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These paths and bowers doubt not but our joint hands.⟦br⟧
Will keep from <qex>wilderness</qex> with ease.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wildfire</ent>⟦br⟧
